The Senate's Democratic and Republican leaders praised President Reagan for retaliatingagainst Japan for violating a semiconducter accord but dashedcold water on ideas it was the first shot in a trade war.    Senate Democratic Leader Robert Byrd and Republican leaderBob Dole both told the Senate Reagan's decision was longoverdue and urged Japan to open its markets to U.S. goods andstop dumping on world markets.    Each noted in separate speeches that they saw no trade warover the issue, despite concerns in financial markets.    "That fear has no basis in fact," Byrd said. Reuter&#3;